Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to
the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the noodles.

Halve the @lime{1/2}. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @carrot{1}, then slice into 1/2cm thick rounds (no need to peel). Trim the
@pak choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Cut any larger leaves in half lengthways down
the middle.

Meanwhile, pop the @chicken gyozas{1%pack} onto a large #baking tray{} and drizzle with
@oil{}. Toss to coat.

Once the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden and crispy, ~{15-18%minutes},
turn halfway through cooking.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{125%g} to the water and cook until tender,
~{4%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them
sticking together.

While the gyozas bake, in a #medium bowl{}, combine the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g},
@peanut butter{30%g}, @soy sauce{15%ml}, @ketjap manis{25%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and
@boiled water{150%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for both amounts).

Stir until well combined.

> TIP: If your peanut butter has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Set aside your Thai style peanut sauce.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Add the carrot and
stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the pak choi to the #pan{}. Stir-fry with the carrot until both veg are tender,
~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}.

When the veg is tender, reduce the heat to medium. Stir through the Thai style peanut
sauce and simmer until slightly reduced, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan and toss to coat in the sauce, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add a squeeze of lime juice, then remove from the heat. Add a splash of water if you
feel it needs it.

Taste and season with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{}, @sugar{} or more lime juice if
needed.

Share the Thai style noodles between your #serving bowls{}.

Top with the crispy chicken gyozas.

Cut any remaining lime into wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!